<div id="review_471114004" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/471114004" />
    <a title="Kerry Hennigan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5941368-kerry-hennigan"><img alt="Kerry Hennigan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1312451719p2/5941368.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/471114004?book_show_action=true">Dec 06, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kerry Hennigan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kerry Hennigan" href="/user/show/5941368-kerry-hennigan">Kerry Hennigan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780007302819" href="/book/show/7117050-the-invisible-mountain">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer471114004" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer807681250464254706">The Invisible Mountain is a sweeping saga of the women of one family and the struggle for freedom from repressive government regimes in various South American countries.<br/><br/>Set primarily in Uruguay, it follows the fortunes of Pajarita, her daughter Eva and finally Salome. Through their experiences, and those of their husbands and brothers and fellow revolutionaries, we travel the tide of history from 1900 through to the last decades of the twentieth century.<br/><br/>But it is Salome’s story that is most comp</span>
  <span id="freeText807681250464254706" style="display:none">The Invisible Mountain is a sweeping saga of the women of one family and the struggle for freedom from repressive government regimes in various South American countries.<br /><br />Set primarily in Uruguay, it follows the fortunes of Pajarita, her daughter Eva and finally Salome. Through their experiences, and those of their husbands and brothers and fellow revolutionaries, we travel the tide of history from 1900 through to the last decades of the twentieth century.<br /><br />But it is Salome’s story that is most compelling; for Salome willingly puts her freedom at risk – and her life – to help the young revolutionaries of Montevideo.<br /><br />The Invisible Mountain provides a fascinating overview of the social and political history of Uruguay and its neighbours in the last century. It is not a novel that is necessarily a quick or easy read, and towards the end I admit that I started to skip through the pages to the climax.<br /><br />Still, I am much the wiser for having read this tale of remarkable women who endure through good times and bad.<br /><br />Kerry Hennigan<br />Dec 6, 2012<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="807681250464254706" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


