    <a title="Doriana Bisegna" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5069712-doriana-bisegna"><img alt="Doriana Bisegna" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/947449518?book_show_action=true">May 25, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Doriana Bisegna" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Doriana Bisegna" href="/user/show/5069712-doriana-bisegna">Doriana Bisegna</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780307456618" href="/book/show/8113215-the-invisible-mountain">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer947449518" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6741850673806885439">To discover a new author and then to be blown away by her debut novel is a major treat for a reader. Carolina De Robertis&apos;s writing is as wonderful as Marquez, Allende and Alvarez. This saga of a South American family spans three generations of women who are all diverse, strong, resilient and powerful in their own way. I love the way the author infused the novel with real history about Uruguay, Cuba and Argentina in the 20th century. This young author is a powerhouse with words and a brilliant s</span>
  <span id="freeText6741850673806885439" style="display:none">To discover a new author and then to be blown away by her debut novel is a major treat for a reader. Carolina De Robertis's writing is as wonderful as Marquez, Allende and Alvarez. This saga of a South American family spans three generations of women who are all diverse, strong, resilient and powerful in their own way. I love the way the author infused the novel with real history about Uruguay, Cuba and Argentina in the 20th century. This young author is a powerhouse with words and a brilliant story maker and teller. Now that the story world has lost Marquez, De Robertis has definitely been shown that she can fill his big shoes and carry the torch of wonderful South American tales.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6741850673806885439" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
